    {
      "layer": 3,
      "layer_name": "Cross-Company Patterns",
      "header": "Deployment & Infrastructure",
      "content": "### Deployment & Infrastructure\n- Stack: Express + PostgreSQL/Neon, deployed on Render\n- Port 10000 standard for Express servers on Render\n- **Render health check endpoint**: Must serve `/health` (not `/api/health`); failed health checks cause silent rollback to previous deploy; place health route at TOP of server.js BEFORE all middleware to ensure instant 200 response; both `/health` and `/api/health` can coexist; enhanced variant tests database connectivity and returns 503 when services degraded; support optional `?check=db` query param to return 503 if database fails; can include database stats (row counts, table sizes, cache stats) for infrastructure monitoring\n- **Trust proxy for rate limiting AND session cookies**: Add `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` immediately after Express app creation, before any middleware; tells Express to trust X-Forwarded-For header from load balancer; rate limiting then sees actual client IPs instead of proxy IP; CRITICAL for session cookie security: Render terminates SSL at load balancer, so Express sees HTTP without this setting, refuses to set `Secure` cookie flag, browser rejects insecure session cookie, user stays logged out despite successful auth → perpetual 401 redirect loops; this breaks magic link flows where auth succeeds momentarily then bounces back to login\n- **Session cookie persistence across auth flows**: OAuth (Google, GitHub) and traditional login/register endpoints MUST explicitly set session cookie via `req.session.save(callback)` before sending response; use atomic `INSERT ... RETURNING id` to prevent concurrent duplicate records; set cookie on OAuth callback AND in traditional login route; verify cookie presence in DevTools after login; magic link sign-up requires same pattern: authenticate on token verification, then persist session cookie before redirecting\n- **Concurrent session tracking schema**: Add `sessions` table (id, user_id, device_id, ip_address, browser_agent, created_at, last_activity, is_active); indexes on user_id + device_id enable multi-device detection; activity timestamp updates on every request detect stale tokens; allows revoking specific device sessions without logging out other devices; password changes invalidate all user sessions for security\n- **Client-side token expiry validation**: Implement SessionManager utility that validates token age before API calls; rejects requests using tokens older than max_age; complements server-side validation\n- **Client-side token storage key consistency**: localStorage token key MUST match across all auth flows (login, register, OAuth callbacks, password reset); mismatched keys cause \"Please log in first\" for logged-in users; verify token key in 3+ places: login write, feature read, logout clear\n- **In-memory session persistence pattern**: Ephemeral sessions (live broadcasts, temporary state) stored in-memory without database backing lose data on deploy restarts; mitigate by: (1) create DB table for session persistence (`live_sessions` table with id, session_id, data, created_at, expires_at), (2) maintain in-memory cache layer (faster, avoids DB round-trips), (3) load cache from DB on startup via `SELECT * FROM live_sessions WHERE expires_at > NOW()`, (4) write-through pattern updates both memory and DB synchronously; prevents production data loss on restart; session tables may require additional domain-specific columns (e.g., `avatar_image_url` for avatar broadcast sessions) to store configuration needed on share page retrieval\n- **Form state persistence across page navigation**: Multi-page sites with forms lose input state on full-page navigation; use sessionStorage with auto-save on input change + restore on page load; sessionStorage cleared after successful submission; prevents user frustration when returning to form after checking pricing/features; enables lightweight persistence without backend dependency\n- **Render build script requirement**: package.json must include \"build\" script; Render runs `npm run build` on deploy and fails without it; script can be no-op (`\"build\": \"echo done\"`) for Node-only apps; migrations run during build step via postbuild hook\n- **Package.json dependency verification**: All `require()` statements must have corresponding entries in package.json dependencies; missing entries cause deploy failures; use `npm install [package] --save` before committing code that imports new modules; dotenv absence breaks all DB connections silently\n- **Route file registration in server.js**: Create routes file but MUST add `require()` statement OR mount via `app.use()` in server.js; missing registration causes \"Cannot GET /route-name\" 404 errors despite file existing; modular route registration enables scalable endpoint organization\n- **SPA-based auth UI route handling**: Auth UI embedded in app.html requires explicit route handlers (`/login`, `/register`, `/signup`, `/forgot-password`, `/reset-password`) serving the SPA file even though auth logic runs client-side; each auth page needs corresponding navigation link from parent pages (homepage, pricing) to be discoverable\n- **Router mount scope isolation**: Auth middleware applied to parent router mount affects ALL child routes; mounting protected routers on `/api` with auth middleware blocks ENTIRE `/api/*` namespace including public endpoints. Solution: scope protected route mounts to `/api/admin` or `/api/protected`, leaving `/api/public` accessible\n- **Custom domain infrastructure workflow**: Domain must be registered on Render service as PREREQUISITE for SSL cert provisioning; DNS resolution alone insufficient; workflow: (1) add domain in Render dashboard (Settings → Custom Domains), (2) Render provides DNS records (A record for apex, CNAME for www), (3) update DNS at registrar with provided records, (4) disable any domain forwarding rules at registrar (overwrites A records), (5) SSL certificate auto-provisions in ~2 min post-DNS propagation; Render dashboard provides exact DNS values — use those instead of generic IPs; custom domain registration with Let's Encrypt takes ~2 minutes post-support/DNS action\n- **Environment variable changes on Render**: Setting/updating env vars via dashboard automatically triggers redeploy; service restarts to pick up new values; no manual deploy trigger needed; changes live in 1-2 minutes\n- **Deploy status lag on Render**: `build_in_progress` or `update_failed` status may persist >8 min despite successful build logs and active app service; wait 5+ min, then trigger manual re-deploy if stuck; verify file size/content changes via curl before assuming stale cache; app logs showing active requests indicate successful deploy despite dashboard status lag\n- **Deploy verification pattern**: Wait 2-3 min post-deploy, curl endpoints to confirm old code gone, verify new features live, test full user flows end-to-end before marking task complete; propagation delays common; version endpoints (`/api/version`) with timestamp markers enable rapid verification that new code is deployed; testing via HTTP instead of HTTPS may trigger 301 redirects misinterpreted as endpoint failures — always verify over HTTPS; CDN/browser cache may show old content for 5-8 minutes despite successful deploy — re-verify after grace period if curl shows stale HTML; WebFetch cache persists 15 minutes, may show stale content even after successful deploy\n- **Incremental feature deployment pattern**: Large features requiring multiple routes/frontend components may timeout single deploy; split into 4 pushes: (1) backend endpoints, (2) middleware fixes, (3) frontend HTML/JS, (4) navigation links; each push 2-3 min apart avoids timeouts\n- **Session store memory leaks**: Express MemoryStore accumulates sessions indefinitely, causing heap growth and eventual OOM crashes on production; replace with PostgreSQL-backed sessions (connect-pg-simple or similar); critical for apps with sustained traffic; implement in staging before production migration\n- **Git directory loss during execution**: `.git` directory can disappear mid-execution on cloud platforms, preventing further git commits/pushes; occurs in environments with volatile filesystems; mitigation: frequent commits to ensure code availability, manual re-initialization if needed\n- **Content rebrand deployment**: Update instance name via infrastructure layer, deploy new URL immediately; old URL decommissioned automatically; meta tags, analytics slugs, documentation, package.json all require coordinated updates; verify new URL responds before marking complete\n- **White-label/rebrand verification**: After removing third-party branding, curl full page content to confirm zero references remain; grep for company name in HTML source; verify tracking domain not in analytics scripts; old content may cache 8+ min post-deploy — wait and re-verify\n- **Infrastructure wind-down workflow**: Preserve data as portfolio report before deletion (company name, revenue, duration, key metrics, failure analysis); delete GitHub repository, Render web service, Neon database, custom domains in sequence; verify all URLs dead after deletion\n- **Third-party SDK initialization guard pattern**: SDKs requiring credentials must check for their presence BEFORE instantiating; SDKs with invalid/dummy credentials often call health checks immediately in constructor which crashes if credentials malformed; pattern: gate SDK constructor with `if (hasCredentials) { initSDK() }` in routes file; allows server to start and other features to function normally\n- **Hardcoded secret fallbacks**: Remove all hardcoded fallback values for sensitive secrets (VAPID keys, encryption keys, API credentials); require environment variables with no defaults; deploy fails immediately if secrets missing, preventing accidental exposure\n- **Feature gating with readiness checks**: Large coordinated deployments use bootstrap guards to prevent downstream features from activating before prerequisites deploy; pattern: (1) deploy foundation with feature disabled via flag, (2) add public health/status endpoint reporting readiness state (what's missing), (3) gate all dependent features with presence checks + feature flags, (4) CI validation prevents dependent code from merging before foundation, (5) deploy foundation PR, (6) safely merge dependent PRs knowing they won't activate; enables parallel development and safe sequential activation\n- **Database foreign key migration order**: FK constraints must reference existing tables; deploy order: parent tables first, then child tables with FKs; reversing order causes migration failures; applies to all schema with relationships (calls → appointments, orders → customers, affiliate programs → tracking links, campaigns → users, grower profiles → inventory, inventory → sites, campaigns → prospects → emails, bookings → customers, ledger usage events → plans, etc.)\n- **Static file routing and SPA entry points**: Express routes must serve correct HTML file for each logical entry point; `/` serves primary landing/app file, secondary routes (`/login`, `/dashboard`, etc.) may serve same SPA file or dedicated HTML files; file placement critical — wrong file at top-level route causes 404s or incorrect UI\n- **Append-only audit ledgers**: Usage tracking, cost metering, billing events use immutable ledger tables with `id, user_id, event_type, amount, created_at` and daily/monthly rollup tables; no updates/deletes on ledger rows; rollups pre-computed for fast dashboard queries; enables audit trail, prevents double-billing, supports billing reconciliation; idempotent recording via unique constraint on `(event_id, user_id)` rejects duplicate submissions; RLS policies on ledgers isolate tenant data in multi-tenant systems",
      "relevance": "73%"
